{"title_page": "Gwyneth", "text_new": "{{Infobox given name\n| name = Gwyneth\n| image=\n| imagesize=\n| caption=\n| pronunciation= {{IPA-cy|\u02c8\u0261w\u0268\u031en\u025b\u03b8|lang}}\n| gender = Feminine\n| meaning = uncertain; first element may be Welsh ''[[wikt:gwyn#Welsh|gwyn]]'' \"white\", but see [[Kingdom of Gwynedd#Etymology|Etymology of ''Gwynedd'']]\n| origin =\n| related names = {{hlist|[[Gwen (given name)|Gwen]]|[[Gwendolyn]]|Gwenith|Gwinnett<ref>http://www.gwinnett.me.uk/characters/george-gwynedd</ref>|Gwenyth|Gwynedd|Venetia}}\n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Gwyneth''' (sometimes '''Gweneth''') is a [[Welsh language|Welsh]] feminine [[given name]] which derives from the kingdom of [[Kingdom of Gwynedd|Gwynedd]]. <!-- The meaning doesn't seem to be known for certain. There exists a Welsh adjective \"gwyn\" that means white (although it has a feminine form \"gwen\"). --> It is borne by the following people:\n*[[Gwyneth Boodoo]], an American psychologist and expert on educational measurement\n*[[Gwyneth Cravens]], an American novelist and journalist\n*[[Gwyneth Dunwoody]] (1930&ndash;2008), a Member of Parliament in the United Kingdom\n*[[Gwyneth Glyn]] (born 1979), a Welsh language poet and musician\n*[[Gwyneth Herbert]] (born 1981), a British singer-songwriter and composer\n*[[Gwyneth Hughes]], British screenwriter and documentary director\n*[[Mabel Gweneth Humphreys]], mathematician\n*[[Gwyneth Johnstone]] (1915\u20132010), English landscape painter\n*[[Gwyneth Jones (novelist)]] (born 1952), a British science fiction and fantasy writer and critic\n*[[Gwyneth Jones (soprano)]] DBE (born 1936), a Welsh soprano\n*[[Gwyneth Lewis]] (born 1959), a Welsh poet, and the first National Poet for Wales\n*[[Gweneth Molony]] (born 1932), Australian figure skater\n*[[Gwyneth Paltrow]] (born 1972), an American actress and businesswoman.\n*[[Gwyneth Powell]] (born 1946), an English actress\n*[[Gwyneth Rees]] (born 1968), a British author of children's books\n*[[Gwyneth Scally]], a visual contemporary artist from Tucson, Arizona, United States\n*[[Gwyneth Stallard]], British mathematician\n*[[Gwyneth Strong]] (born 1959), an English actress\n*[[Gwyneth Walker]] (born 1947), an American composer\n*[[Gwenethe Walshe]] (1908 \u2013 2006), British dancer \n*[[Gweneth Whitteridge]], medical historian\n\n'''Gwyneth''' is also the name of the following fictional characters:\n*a character in the ''[[Fur Fighters]]'' video game\n*the title character of ''Gwyneth and the Thief'', a young adult historical romance novel written by [[Margaret Moore]]\n*Gwyneth, a character in the Dragonlance novel ''[[The Legend of Huma]]''\n*Gwynneth, an Australian Masked Owl from the [[Guardians of Ga'Hoole#Wolves Of The Beyond|Wolves of the Beyond]] fantasy novel series by Kathryn Lasky\n\n==See also==\n* [[Gwynedd (disambiguation)]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{given name}}\n\n[[Category:English feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Scottish feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Welsh feminine given names]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox given name\n| name = Gwyneth\n| image=\n| imagesize=\n| caption=\n| pronunciation= {{IPA-cy|\u02c8\u0261w\u0268\u031en\u025b\u03b8|lang}}\n| gender = Feminine\n| meaning = uncertain; first element may be Welsh ''[[wikt:gwyn#Welsh|gwyn]]'' \"white\", but see [[Kingdom of Gwynedd#Etymology|Etymology of ''Gwynedd'']]\n| origin =\n| related names = {{hlist|[[Gwen (given name)|Gwen]]|[[Gwendolyn]]|Gwenith|Gwinnett<ref>http://www.gwinnett.me.uk/characters/george-gwynedd</ref>|Gwenyth|Gwynedd|Venetia}}\n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''Gwyneth''' (sometimes '''Gweneth''') is a [[Welsh language|Welsh]] feminine [[given name]] which derives from the kingdom of [[Kingdom_of_Gwynedd|Gwynedd]]. <!-- The meaning doesn't seem to be known for certain. There exists a Welsh adjective \"gwyn\" that means white (although it has a feminine form \"gwen\"). --> It is borne by the following people:\n*[[Gwyneth Boodoo]], an American psychologist and expert on educational measurement\n*[[Gwyneth Cravens]], an American novelist and journalist\n*[[Gwyneth Dunwoody]] (1930&ndash;2008), a Member of Parliament in the United Kingdom\n*[[Gwyneth Glyn]] (born 1979), a Welsh language poet and musician\n*[[Gwyneth Herbert]] (born 1981), a British singer-songwriter and composer\n*[[Gwyneth Hughes]], British screenwriter and documentary director\n*[[Mabel Gweneth Humphreys]], mathematician\n*[[Gwyneth Johnstone]] (1915\u20132010), English landscape painter\n*[[Gwyneth Jones (novelist)]] (born 1952), a British science fiction and fantasy writer and critic\n*[[Gwyneth Jones (soprano)]] DBE (born 1936), a Welsh soprano\n*[[Gwyneth Lewis]] (born 1959), a Welsh poet, and the first National Poet for Wales\n*[[Gweneth Molony]] (born 1932), Australian figure skater\n*[[Gwyneth Paltrow]] (born 1972), an American actress and businesswoman.\n*[[Gwyneth Powell]] (born 1946), an English actress\n*[[Gwyneth Rees]] (born 1968), a British author of children's books\n*[[Gwyneth Scally]], a visual contemporary artist from Tucson, Arizona, United States\n*[[Gwyneth Stallard]], British mathematician\n*[[Gwyneth Strong]] (born 1959), an English actress\n*[[Gwyneth Walker]] (born 1947), an American composer\n*[[Gwenethe Walshe]] (1908 \u2013 2006), British dancer \n*[[Gweneth Whitteridge]], medical historian\n\n'''Gwyneth''' is also the name of the following fictional characters:\n*a character in the ''[[Fur Fighters]]'' video game\n*the title character of ''Gwyneth and the Thief'', a young adult historical romance novel written by [[Margaret Moore]]\n*Gwyneth, a character in the Dragonlance novel ''[[The Legend of Huma]]''\n*Gwynneth, an Australian Masked Owl from the [[Guardians of Ga'Hoole#Wolves Of The Beyond|Wolves of the Beyond]] fantasy novel series by Kathryn Lasky\n\n==See also==\n* [[Gwynedd (disambiguation)]]\n\n{{given name}}\n\n[[Category:English feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Scottish feminine given names]]\n[[Category:Welsh feminine given